<section id="sources">
  <p class="section-label">Our Library and Sources</p>
  <h2 class="section-title">Two thousand years<br>of Christian counsel.</h2>
  <div class="divider"></div>
  <p class="section-body">Every counselor draws from Scripture and a curated library of historic Christian pastoral and theological writings &mdash; voices from the early church, the Reformation, the Puritans, and the great evangelical tradition that followed.</p>
  <div class="library-grid">

    <div class="library-card">
      <h3 class="library-tradition">Scripture</h3>
      <ul class="library-list">
        <li>The Holy Bible &mdash; the full New Testament, plus the Psalms, Proverbs, Isaiah, Job, Ecclesiastes, Song of Solomon, and Genesis 1&ndash;11</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="library-card">
      <h3 class="library-tradition">The Early Church</h3>
      <ul class="library-list">
        <li>Augustine of Hippo &mdash; <em>Confessions</em>; <em>On Christian Doctrine</em></li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="library-card">
      <h3 class="library-tradition">The Reformation</h3>
      <ul class="library-list">
        <li>Letters and devotional writings of the Reformation (Luther's correspondence, Calvin's Golden Booklet and Psalms commentary)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="library-card">
      <h3 class="library-tradition">Confessions &amp; Catechisms</h3>
      <ul class="library-list">
        <li>The 1689 Baptist Confession of Faith</li>
        <li>The Westminster Confession and Catechisms (Larger and Shorter)</li>
        <li>The Three Forms of Unity</li>
        <li>The Heidelberg Catechism</li>
        <li>Keach's Catechism (1677)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="library-card">
      <h3 class="library-tradition">The Puritans</h3>
      <ul class="library-list">
        <li>John Bunyan &mdash; <em>The Pilgrim's Progress</em>; <em>Grace Abounding</em></li>
        <li>John Flavel &mdash; <em>Keeping the Heart</em></li>
        <li>John Owen &mdash; <em>The Mortification of Sin</em></li>
        <li>Richard Sibbes &mdash; <em>The Bruised Reed</em></li>
        <li>Thomas Watson &mdash; <em>All Things for Good</em></li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="library-card">
      <h3 class="library-tradition">The Evangelical &amp; Pastoral Tradition</h3>
      <ul class="library-list">
        <li>Jonathan Edwards &mdash; <em>Religious Affections</em></li>
        <li>Andrew Murray &mdash; <em>With Christ in the School of Prayer</em>; <em>Absolute Surrender</em>; <em>The True Vine</em></li>
        <li>J. C. Ryle &mdash; <em>Holiness</em>; <em>Expository Thoughts on the Gospels (Matthew)</em></li>
        <li>Charles Spurgeon &mdash; <em>Morning and Evening</em>; <em>The Treasury of David</em>; <em>Faith's Checkbook</em>; <em>All of Grace</em>; <em>Till He Come</em></li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="library-card">
      <h3 class="library-tradition">Modern Pastoral</h3>
      <ul class="library-list">
        <li>Selected devotional writings of Paul David Tripp</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

  </div>
  <p class="library-closing">When you bring a question, your counselor draws from this library &mdash; the historic voice of the church speaking to your situation &mdash; and weaves it together with Scripture to point you to Christ, the Great Physician.</p>
</section>

<section id="library-articles">
  <p class="section-label">Theology &amp; Ministry</p>
  <h2 class="section-title">From the Library.</h2>
  <div class="divider"></div>
  <p class="section-body">Theological papers and longer-form articles exploring the biblical and doctrinal foundations of soul care — written for pastors, counselors, and thoughtful Christians.</p>
  <div class="blog-grid" style="margin-top: 60px;">

    <a class="blog-card" href="library/the-image-and-the-instrument.html">
      <div class="blog-date">Theology of Technology · Herman Bavinck</div>
      <div class="blog-title">The Image and the Instrument</div>
      <div class="blog-excerpt">What can AI do in the care of souls — and what is it constitutionally incapable of doing? Drawing on Bavinck's <em>Philosophy of Revelation</em> and <em>Christian Worldview</em>, a theological account of the distinction between the image-bearer and the artifact.</div>
      <span class="blog-read-more">Read Article →</span>
    </a>

    <a class="blog-card" href="library/nothing-new-under-the-sun.html">
      <div class="blog-date">Theology of Technology · Ecclesiastes · Bavinck</div>
      <div class="blog-title">Nothing New Under the Sun</div>
      <div class="blog-excerpt">AI is powerful, unprecedented in form, and exactly what Bavinck would have predicted. Following his epistemological ascent from sense perception to divine ideas, a Reformed account of what artificial intelligence is — and where it stops.</div>
      <span class="blog-read-more">Read Article →</span>
    </a>

    <a class="blog-card" href="library/what-it-means-to-be-human-part1.html">
      <div class="blog-date">Biblical Anthropology · Series Part 1 of 3</div>
      <div class="blog-title">Crowned with Glory</div>
      <div class="blog-excerpt">What does it mean to be made in the image of God? A biblical and Reformed account of human dignity, original righteousness, and the vocation of image-bearing — drawn from Scripture, Calvin, Bavinck, and the Puritans.</div>
      <span class="blog-read-more">Read Article →</span>
    </a>

    <a class="blog-card" href="library/what-it-means-to-be-human-part2.html">
      <div class="blog-date">Biblical Anthropology · Series Part 2 of 3</div>
      <div class="blog-title">The Wound at the Root</div>
      <div class="blog-excerpt">What has sin done to the image of God in man? A biblical and Reformed account of the fall, original sin, total depravity, and the depth of human corruption — and why the diagnosis must be deep enough to reach the cure.</div>
      <span class="blog-read-more">Read Article →</span>
    </a>

  </div>
</section>

