    </div>

    <div class="article-body">

      <p>The anxiety about artificial intelligence is real, widespread, and — in its better forms — theologically serious. It deserves a serious answer. This essay offers one, drawn not from the latest headlines or the most recent academic commentary on AI ethics, but from a Dutch Reformed theologian who died in 1921 and who saw the crisis coming more clearly than most of his contemporaries.</p>

      <p>Herman Bavinck did not write about artificial intelligence. He wrote about something more fundamental: the question of where human knowledge comes from, what it can reach, and what lies permanently beyond its grasp. His answer provides a framework that locates AI precisely on the map of human knowing — neither dismissing its genuine power nor mistaking it for something it can never be.</p>

